{% import "product-components.njk" as pc %}
<section class="intro-section mb-12">
  <h3 id="mission">Mission</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Web Positioning</strong> standardizes <strong>anchoring</strong> — placing a floating element
    (tooltip, popover, menu) relative to another element and keeping it tethered there as the page
    scrolls and resizes. It defines the contract (via the <a href="/intents/">Anchor Intent</a>), a
    shared <a href="/plugs/custompositioningregistry/">positioning provider</a> that components delegate
    to, and <a href="/projects/webadapters/">adapters</a> that let an existing engine (Floating UI) or
    the native platform fulfil that contract.
  </p>
  <p>
    It is <strong>native-first</strong>: the default provider leans on
    <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/Guides/Anchor_positioning">CSS Anchor Positioning</a>
    (Baseline 2026) and the <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Popover_API">Popover API</a>.
    Third-party libraries are opt-in enhancements through adapters — not the baseline dependency.
  </p>

  <div class="comparison-block" style="background: rgba(5, 150, 105, 0.08); padding: 1.25rem; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #059669; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #047857; font-size: 1rem;">The problem it solves</h4>
    <p style="margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
      You import ten components from different vendors — a date picker, a combobox, a tooltip, a menu —
      and <strong>every one of them ships its own positioning engine</strong>. Web Positioning lets the
      application register <strong>one</strong> provider that all of them resolve and delegate to, so the
      bundle carries a single engine instead of ten copies of the same collision math.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

{{ pc.standardSection('id="features"') }}
  <h3 id="feature-surface">Feature Surface</h3>
  <p>
    What a positioning standard covers, and how each capability is fulfilled. <strong>Built-in</strong> = the
    bundled native-first provider; <strong>Adapter</strong> = delegated to a plugged-in library (Floating UI);
    <strong>Compose</strong> = deferred to an existing Web Everything standard rather than reimplemented.
  </p>
