{{ pc.standardSection('id="protocol-anchor-positioning"') }}
  <h3 id="how-it-works">Anchor Positioning Protocol</h3>
  <p>
    A component never bundles a positioning engine. It declares its <a href="/intents/">Anchor Intent</a>,
    resolves the application's provider through the injector chain, and delegates the math:
  </p>
  {% highlight "typescript" %}
// 1. The application registers ONE provider (native-first by default).
import { FloatingUIAdapter } from '@web-adapters/floating-ui';
customPositioning.define('floating-ui', new FloatingUIAdapter());

injector Application {
  // every descendant component resolves this provider
  provide { positioning: 'floating-ui' } to '@web-positioning';
}

// 2. Any vendor component delegates — it does not know which engine runs.
const provider = InjectorRoot.getProviderOf(el, 'customPositioning');
const cleanup = provider.position(anchorEl, floatingEl, {
  placement: 'bottom-start',
  collision: ['flip', 'shift'],
  tracking: 'follow',          // recompute on scroll/resize
});
// cleanup() detaches listeners when the floating element closes
  {% endhighlight %}
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted); margin-top: 1rem;">
    <li><strong>One contract:</strong> the <a href="/plugs/custompositioner/"><code>CustomPositioner</code></a> interface — <code>position(anchor, anchored, options): Cleanup</code> — is satisfied by the native default and by every adapter alike.</li>
    <li><strong>One registry:</strong> <a href="/plugs/custompositioningregistry/"><code>CustomPositioningRegistry</code></a> (<code>window.customPositioning</code>) holds the named providers.</li>
    <li><strong>Injector resolution:</strong> components get the app-configured provider, so swapping engines is a one-line change with zero component edits.</li>
  </ul>
{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}

{{ pc.standardSection('id="composition"') }}
  <h3 id="composition">Composition With Other Standards</h3>
  <p>
    Web Positioning owns <em>where</em> a floating element sits, not <em>how it escapes the DOM</em> or
    <em>how high it stacks</em> — those compose with neighbouring standards, mirroring how CSS separates
    positioning from layering:
  </p>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem;">
    <li><strong><a href="/projects/webportals/">Web Portals</a></strong> — the <code>escape</code> strategy lifts a floating element to the top layer / out of clipping ancestors.</li>
    <li><strong>Surface Intent</strong> — elevation and z-stacking of the floating surface.</li>
    <li><strong>Modal / View blocks</strong> — light dismiss, focus trapping, open/close lifecycle.</li>
  </ul>
{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}

{{ pc.standardSection('id="status"') }}
  <h3 id="status">Status</h3>
  <p>
    Web Positioning is in <strong>concept</strong> phase. The contract and provider registry are specified;
    the native-first default provider and the Floating UI adapter are the first planned implementations.
  </p>
  <h4 style="margin-top: 1rem;">Open Questions</h4>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
    <li>How deep should the <code>escape</code> strategy delegate to Web Portals vs. drive the native Popover top layer directly?</li>
    <li>Arrow placement math — built-in basic vs. always defer to an adapter?</li>
    <li>RTL and safe-area (notch / virtual keyboard) handling in the native default provider.</li>
  </ul>
{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}
